===========================================================


After uploading your Laravel project to a server, you need to configure it before it will run in the browser.

1. Point the web server to the public folder

Your web server's document root should point to:

/home/username/your-project/public

Apache VirtualHost example:

DocumentRoot /var/www/your-project/public

<Directory /var/www/your-project/public>
    AllowOverride All
    Require all granted
</Directory>

Nginx example:

root /var/www/your-project/public;
index index.php index.html;
2. Configure the .env file

Edit the .env file:

APP_NAME=Laravel
APP_ENV=production
APP_DEBUG=false
APP_URL=https://yourdomain.com

DB_CONNECTION=mysql
DB_HOST=localhost
DB_PORT=3306
DB_DATABASE=your_database
DB_USERNAME=your_username
DB_PASSWORD=your_password

Replace the database values with your actual credentials.

3. Install dependencies

If the vendor folder is missing, run:

composer install --no-dev --optimize-autoloader
4. Generate the application key (if needed)
php artisan key:generate
5. Run database migrations
php artisan migrate
6. Set permissions

On Linux:

chmod -R 775 storage bootstrap/cache

or

chown -R www-data:www-data storage bootstrap/cache
7. Clear and rebuild caches
php artisan optimize:clear
php artisan config:cache
php artisan route:cache
php artisan view:cache
8. Open your website

Visit:

https://yourdomain.com

or, if it's in a subfolder:

https://yourdomain.com/your-project/public
If you're using shared hosting (cPanel)
Upload the Laravel project outside public_html (for example, /home/username/laravel-app).
Copy the contents of the project's public folder into public_html.
Update the paths in public_html/index.php to point to the Laravel project:
require __DIR__.'/../laravel-app/vendor/autoload.php';

$app = require_once __DIR__.'/../laravel-app/bootstrap/app.php';
